import csv
from Bio import AlignIO
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from Bio.Phylo.TreeConstruction import DistanceCalculator
In [7]:
def get_sequence_names(sample):
    # Read the alignment from the FASTA file corresponding to the sample
    alignment = AlignIO.read("data/fasta/aligned/" + sample + "_aligned.fasta", "fasta")
    # Extract sequence names (IDs) from the alignment
    sequence_names = [record.id for record in alignment]
    # Return the sequence names 
    return sequence_names
In [12]:
def compute_distance_matrix(sample):
    # Read the alignment from the FASTA file corresponding to the sample
    alignment = AlignIO.read("data/fasta/aligned/" + sample + "_aligned.fasta", "fasta")
    # Initialize the distance calculator with 'blastn' method
    calculator = DistanceCalculator('blastn')
    # Compute the distance matrix for the given alignment
    distance_matrix = calculator.get_distance(alignment)
    # Return the distance matrix 
    return distance_matrix
In [13]:
def save_distance_matrix(distance_matrix, file_path):
    # Convert Distance Matrix to list of lists
    matrix_list = distance_matrix.matrix
    with open(file_path + ".csv", 'w', newline='') as file:
        writer = csv.writer(file)
        # Write the header
        writer.writerow([''] + distance_matrix.names)
        # Write the rows
        for name, row in zip(distance_matrix.names, matrix_list):
            writer.writerow([name] + row)
In [18]:
def plot_distance_matrices(samples):
    # Define the dimensions for the figure
    figure_width = 9
    figure_height = 6
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=5, ncols=2, figsize=(2 * figure_width, 5 * figure_height))
    
    # Loop through each sample and the corresponding subplot axis
    for sample, ax in zip(samples, axes.ravel()):
        
        # Get sequence names and distance matrix for the current sample
        sequence_names = get_sequence_names(sample)
        distance_matrix = compute_distance_matrix(sample)
        # Save distance matrix
        save_distance_matrix(distance_matrix, "data/distance_matrices/" + sample + "_distance_matrix")
        # Plot the distance matrix as a heatmap
        heatmap = ax.imshow(distance_matrix, cmap='coolwarm', aspect='auto')
        # Add a colorbar to indicate distance values
        colorbar = fig.colorbar(heatmap, ax=ax, label="Distance")
        
        # Set x-axis and y-axis ticks and labels
        ax.set_xticks(ticks=range(len(sequence_names)))
        ax.set_xticklabels(sequence_names, rotation=90)
        ax.set_yticks(ticks=range(len(sequence_names)))
        ax.set_yticklabels(sequence_names)
        
        # Set the title for the subplot
        ax.set_title(f"Family {sample[0:2]}", fontsize=12, weight='bold')
        
        # Overlay the distance values on the heatmap
        for i in range(len(sequence_names)):
            for j in range(len(sequence_names)):
                ax.text(j, i, f"{distance_matrix[i][j]:.2f}", ha='center', va='center', color='black')
        
    # Adjust the layout to make sure elements don't overlap
    plt.tight_layout()
    # Save the plot to a file
    plt.savefig("fig/figure_distance_matrices_families.pdf", format='pdf', dpi=300, bbox_inches='tight')
    # Display the plot
    plt.show()
